{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe audit UI needs an optional, disabled-by-default, read-only local web surface that is fully inert\nwhen off. Establishing that surface — the packaging extra, the config flag (with ALL its wiring), lazy\nimports, the loopback binding, and a running server that renders one real page end-to-end — is the\nriskiest architectural piece (gating + packaging + binding), so it ships first as a thin vertical\nslice that proves the whole optional-surface mechanism.\n\n## What\n\nA `rebar audit serve` subcommand that, when enabled, starts a FastAPI server (reusing the `reviewbot`\nweb stack) bound to 127.0.0.1, serving a read-only INDEX page listing tickets that have audit data\n(each linking to a per-ticket page that the sibling rendering story fills in). Gated by a new\ndefault-false `[ui] enabled` config flag and a new `nava-rebar[ui]` optional extra; all web imports\nare lazy so disabled / absent-extra = inert. Default port `8765`.\n\n## Endpoint access contract (human/admin auth)\n\nThe server binds 127.0.0.1 (loopback) ONLY and serves READ-ONLY content; there is no state-changing\nendpoint. Human access control is the loopback boundary — no network principal can reach it — the\njustified no-auth posture (matching datasette / mlflow / `git instaweb --local`). Binding a\nnon-loopback host requires an explicit `--host` flag that prints a warning to stderr; actually\nexposing the service to a network (and any auth then required) is OUT of scope for this epic —\ndocumented, not implemented. No machine credentials are involved.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `pyproject.toml` — add `[project.optional-dependencies] ui = [\"fastapi\", \"uvicorn[standard]\",\n  \"jinja2\"]` (reusing the reviewbot stack); document the extra.\n- `src/rebar/_config_schema.py` — the FULL `UiConfig` wiring (a partial edit is silently dropped as an\n  unknown section by `coerce_sparse`): (1) add a `UiConfig` dataclass with `enabled: bool = False`;\n  (2) add `ui: UiConfig = field(default_factory=UiConfig)` to the top-level `Config` dataclass;\n  (3) register `\"ui\": UiConfig` in `_SECTION_CLASSES`; (4) add `\"ui\": {\"enabled\": lambda v, k:\n  _as_bool(v, k)}` to the `_SECTIONS` coercer map — yielding env override `REBAR_UI_ENABLED`.\n- `src/rebar/config.py` — re-export `UiConfig` (this module re-exports every `_config_schema` class);\n  document the key in `docs/config.md`.\n- New `src/rebar/audit/server.py` (< 500 LOC) — the FastAPI app + a `serve(host, port)` entry,\n  lazy-imported inside the CLI handler with a friendly \"install nava-rebar[ui]\" `SystemExit` on\n  `ModuleNotFoundError`; binds 127.0.0.1 by default; one index route using the read layer from story E.\n- CLI: register `audit` as an INTERCEPT in `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py::main` (mirroring the\n  `workflow`/`llm`/`explain` intercepts — an `if argv and argv[0] == \"audit\": return _audit(argv[1:])`\n  arm that owns its own `--help`). This is the intercept convention: NO `help/*.txt` file and NO\n  `known_subcommands` change (that set is auto-derived from `_cli/help/*.txt` and is only for\n  golden-captured subcommands, which intercepts deliberately are not). `_audit` dispatches\n  `serve`/`show`.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\nReuse the reviewbot FastAPI/uvicorn stack rather than adding Flask or a bespoke `http.server`, so the\nrepo carries one web framework; lazy-import it inside the command (never at package init) so\n`import rebar` stays dependency-free — the pattern the reviewbot extra already proves. Register as an\nintercept (like `workflow`/`llm`) because `audit` owns a nested command grammar (`serve`/`show`) and\nits own `--help`, which the golden-captured `help/*.txt` subcommands do not. Ship a thin vertical slice\n(server + one real index page) so the risky packaging/gating/binding path is exercised end-to-end from\nthe first story.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nDefault-off and behind an extra; `import rebar` unchanged. The `[ui]` section is additive (absent\n`[ui]` defaults to `enabled=False`). Rollback = flag off / extra not installed. No data/schema change.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `[ui] enabled` round-trips through config via `rebar.toml`, `REBAR_UI_ENABLED`, and\n      `-c ui.enabled=...`, each yielding `Config.ui.enabled == True`, and is NOT reported as an unknown\n      key. Oracle: a unit test loading config through all three paths and asserting the value + absence\n      of the \"unknown key ignored\" warning.\n- [ ] With `[ui] enabled = false` (default), `import rebar` imports no web dependency and\n      `rebar audit serve` refuses to start with a message naming the flag. Oracle: a test asserting no\n      fastapi module is imported by `import rebar` and the disabled path does not start a server.\n- [ ] With the `ui` extra absent, `rebar audit serve` exits with an actionable \"install\n      nava-rebar[ui]\" message, not a traceback. Oracle: a unit test simulating `ModuleNotFoundError`\n      on the lazy import and asserting the message + non-zero exit.\n- [ ] `rebar audit serve --host 0.0.0.0` prints a non-loopback exposure warning to stderr before\n      binding; `--host 127.0.0.1` (default) does not. Oracle: a CLI test asserting the warning's\n      presence/absence per host.\n- [ ] With the feature enabled, the server binds 127.0.0.1 and serves an index page listing tickets\n      that have audit data. Oracle: a live end-to-end test starting the server on an ephemeral port and\n      asserting the index returns HTTP 200 and lists a seeded audited ticket (test-design §3\n      server/CLI).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784081193473611001,"uuid":"a0a99841-4357-43de-9ce7-b0885305f6cf"}